Create a `cc.Layer` instance and add it to a `cc.Scene`. `cc.Layer` extends `cc.Node` and serves as a container for organizing scene hierarchy:

```typescript
const scene = new cc.Scene();
const layer = new cc.Layer();
scene.addChild(layer);
cc.director.runScene(scene);

// Add children to the layer
const sprite = new cc.Sprite('res/hero.png');
sprite.setPosition(240, 160);
layer.addChild(sprite);
```

`cc.Layer` is the base layer class â€” use it as a container to group nodes logically. You can add multiple layers to a scene at different z-orders to control rendering order.

Use the `cc.LayerColor` constructor with a `cc.Color` argument:

```typescript
// Full-screen black background
const bg = new cc.LayerColor(cc.color(0, 0, 0, 255));
scene.addChild(bg, -1);

// Custom-sized red layer
const redBox = new cc.LayerColor(cc.color(255, 0, 0, 255), 200, 100);
redBox.setPosition(100, 100);
this.addChild(redBox);

// Using static factory method
const blueLayer = cc.LayerColor.create(cc.color(0, 0, 255, 255));
this.addChild(blueLayer);
```

`cc.LayerColor` extends `cc.Layer` and draws a solid color rectangle. The constructor accepts `(color)` for a full-screen layer, or `(color, width, height)` for a custom-sized one. Color values use RGBA 0â€“255 range.

Pass a `cc.Color` with an alpha value less than 255 to create a semi-transparent overlay:

```typescript
// 50% transparent black overlay
const overlay = new cc.LayerColor(cc.color(0, 0, 0, 128));
overlay.setContentSize(cc.director.getWinSize());
this.addChild(overlay, 10);  // high z-order to render on top
```

The alpha channel (fourth parameter of `cc.color`) controls transparency: 255 is fully opaque, 0 is fully transparent, and 128 gives roughly 50% transparency. This pattern is commonly used for pause screens, dialog backgrounds, or dimming effects.

Use `cc.LayerGradient` with start color, end color, and an optional direction vector:

```typescript
// Vertical gradient: blue (top) to dark blue (bottom)
const grad = new cc.LayerGradient(
    cc.color(30, 100, 200, 255),   // start color
    cc.color(5, 15, 40, 255),      // end color
    cc.p(0, -1)                     // direction: downward
);
scene.addChild(grad, -1);

// Horizontal gradient: red to yellow
const horizGrad = new cc.LayerGradient(
    cc.color(255, 0, 0, 255),
    cc.color(255, 255, 0, 255),
    cc.p(1, 0)                      // direction: left to right
);
scene.addChild(horizGrad, -1);

// Using factory method
const grad2 = cc.LayerGradient.create(
    cc.color(0, 0, 0, 255),
    cc.color(255, 255, 255, 255)
);
```

The third parameter is a `cc.Point` defining the gradient direction. `cc.p(0, -1)` goes top-to-bottom, `cc.p(1, 0)` goes left-to-right. Without a direction vector, the gradient defaults to vertical.

Use the setter methods or direct property access to modify gradient colors and opacity at runtime:

```typescript
const grad = new cc.LayerGradient(
    cc.color(255, 0, 0, 255),
    cc.color(0, 0, 255, 255)
);
this.addChild(grad);

// Using setter methods
grad.setStartColor(cc.color(0, 255, 0, 255));
grad.setEndColor(cc.color(255, 255, 0, 255));
grad.setStartOpacity(255);
grad.setEndOpacity(128);
grad.setVector(cc.p(1, -1));  // diagonal direction

// Using properties
grad.startColor = cc.color(100, 50, 200, 255);
grad.endColor = cc.color(20, 10, 50, 255);
grad.startOpacity = 255;
grad.endOpacity = 200;

// Read current values
const start = grad.getStartColor();
const end = grad.getEndColor();
const dir = grad.getVector();
```

Opacity values range from 0â€“255. The vector changes the gradient direction without recreating the layer.

Create a `cc.LayerMultiplex` with multiple layers, then use `switchTo` to show one at a time:

```typescript
const mainLayer = new cc.Layer();
const settingsLayer = new cc.Layer();
const inventoryLayer = new cc.Layer();

// Create multiplex with initial layers
const multiplex = new cc.LayerMultiplex(mainLayer, settingsLayer, inventoryLayer);
scene.addChild(multiplex);

// Show main (index 0) â€” this is the default
multiplex.switchTo(0);

// Switch to settings (index 1)
multiplex.switchTo(1);

// Switch to inventory (index 2)
multiplex.switchTo(2);

// Add a new layer dynamically
const shopLayer = new cc.Layer();
multiplex.addLayer(shopLayer);
multiplex.switchTo(3);  // switch to shop
```

`switchTo(n)` removes the currently visible layer and shows layer at index `n`. Only one layer is visible and active at a time. Use `switchToAndReleaseMe(n)` if you want to also release the current layer's memory.

These three classes form an inheritance chain, each adding visual capabilities:

**`cc.Layer`** (extends `cc.Node`)
- Transparent container, no visual rendering
- Used to group and organize nodes in scene hierarchy
- Supports `bake()`/`unbake()` for HTML5 performance optimization

**`cc.LayerColor`** (extends `cc.Layer`)
- Draws a solid color rectangle
- Has width/height control and blend functions
- Useful for backgrounds, overlays, and UI panels

**`cc.LayerGradient`** (extends `cc.LayerColor`)
- Draws a two-color gradient
- Adds start/end color, opacity, and direction vector
- Useful for sky backgrounds, UI effects

```typescript
// Invisible container
const container = new cc.Layer();

// Solid black background
const solid = new cc.LayerColor(cc.color(0, 0, 0, 255));

// Blue-to-black gradient
const gradient = new cc.LayerGradient(
    cc.color(30, 100, 200, 255),
    cc.color(5, 15, 40, 255),
    cc.p(0, -1)
);
```

Since `cc.LayerGradient` extends `cc.LayerColor`, it inherits all color layer methods like `changeWidth`, `changeHeight`, and `setBlendFunc`.

`bake()` and `unbake()` are HTML5-only performance optimization methods on `cc.Layer`:

```typescript
class GameLayer extends cc.Layer {
    constructor() {
        super();
        this.init();
    }

    init(): boolean {
        // Add many static children
        for (let i = 0; i < 100; i++) {
            const tile = new cc.Sprite('res/tile.png');
            tile.setPosition(i * 16, 0);
            this.addChild(tile);
        }

        // Cache all children into a single bake sprite
        this.bake();
        return true;
    }

    onChildrenChanged(): void {
        // Unbake to allow changes, then re-bake
        this.unbake();
        // ... modify children ...
        this.bake();
    }
}

// Check if currently baked
const isBaked: boolean = layer.isBaked();
```

`bake()` renders all children into a cached sprite texture, so the entire layer is drawn as a single image instead of many individual draw calls. This significantly improves performance for layers with many static children (like tile maps or static UI). Call `unbake()` before modifying children, then `bake()` again. `isBaked()` returns the current state. These methods only work on HTML5 â€” they are no-ops on native platforms.

Use `changeWidth`, `changeHeight`, or `changeWidthAndHeight` to resize a `cc.LayerColor` at runtime:

```typescript
const colorLayer = new cc.LayerColor(cc.color(255, 0, 0, 255), 100, 50);
this.addChild(colorLayer);

// Change only width
colorLayer.changeWidth(200);

// Change only height
colorLayer.changeHeight(100);

// Change both at once
colorLayer.changeWidthAndHeight(300, 150);

// You can also use setContentSize (inherited from cc.Node)
colorLayer.setContentSize(cc.size(400, 200));
```

`changeWidthAndHeight` is more efficient than calling `changeWidth` and `changeHeight` separately since it updates the layer in a single operation. These methods are specific to `cc.LayerColor` and its subclass `cc.LayerGradient`.

Use `setBlendFunc` to control how the layer's color blends with the content behind it:

```typescript
const overlay = new cc.LayerColor(cc.color(255, 255, 255, 128));
this.addChild(overlay, 10);

// Set blend function with individual constants
overlay.setBlendFunc(cc.SRC_ALPHA, cc.ONE_MINUS_SRC_ALPHA);

// Or pass a BlendFunc object
overlay.setBlendFunc({ src: cc.SRC_ALPHA, dst: cc.ONE });

// Read the current blend function
const blend = overlay.getBlendFunc();
cc.log('src: ' + blend.src + ', dst: ' + blend.dst);
```

Common blend modes:
- `cc.SRC_ALPHA, cc.ONE_MINUS_SRC_ALPHA` â€” standard alpha blending (default)
- `cc.SRC_ALPHA, cc.ONE` â€” additive blending (bright glow effect)
- `cc.ZERO, cc.SRC_COLOR` â€” multiply blending

`setBlendFunc` is available on `cc.LayerColor` and `cc.LayerGradient`.

`switchToAndReleaseMe(n)` switches to layer at index `n` AND releases (frees memory of) the currently displayed layer:

```typescript
const mainLayer = new cc.Layer();
const tutorialLayer = new cc.Layer();
const multiplex = new cc.LayerMultiplex(mainLayer, tutorialLayer);
scene.addChild(multiplex);

// Show tutorial first
multiplex.switchTo(1);

// Switch to main and release tutorial (one-time screen)
multiplex.switchToAndReleaseMe(0);
// tutorialLayer is now released and cannot be switched back to
```

**`switchTo(n)`** â€” shows layer `n`, hides current. The current layer remains in memory and can be switched back to later.

**`switchToAndReleaseMe(n)`** â€” shows layer `n`, removes AND releases the current layer. Use this when the current layer won't be needed again (e.g., one-time tutorial, loading screen).

Use `switchTo` for screens you revisit (main menu, settings). Use `switchToAndReleaseMe` for one-time screens to save memory.

```typescript
class GameLayer extends cc.Layer {
    private hero: cc.Sprite;
    private speed: number = 100;

    constructor() {
        super();
        this.init();
    }

    init(): boolean {
        const winSize = cc.director.getWinSize();

        this.hero = new cc.Sprite('res/hero.png');
        this.hero.setPosition(winSize.width / 2, winSize.height / 2);
        this.addChild(this.hero);

        this.scheduleUpdate();
        return true;
    }

    update(dt: number): void {
        const pos = this.hero.getPosition();
        this.hero.setPositionX(pos.x + this.speed * dt);

        const winSize = cc.director.getWinSize();
        if (this.hero.getPositionX() > winSize.width) {
            this.hero.setPositionX(0);
        }
    }
}

const scene = new cc.Scene();
scene.addChild(new GameLayer());
cc.director.runScene(scene);
```

The class extends `cc.Layer`, creates a sprite in `init()`, enables the update loop with `scheduleUpdate()`, and moves the hero each frame in `update(dt)`. The `dt` parameter is the delta time in seconds since the last frame.

