loading.setProgress(45);
```

The progress bar uses `cc.LayerColor` for the dark background track and `cc.LayerGradient` for a green gradient fill. The gradient direction `cc.p(1, 0)` goes left-to-right, creating a nice color transition as the bar fills. `changeWidth` resizes the fill dynamically.

Layers and their children are cleaned up automatically when a scene is replaced, but here are best practices:

```typescript
class GameLayer extends cc.Layer {
    private scheduledCallbacks: Function[] = [];

    init(): boolean {
        this.scheduleUpdate();
        return true;
    }

    onExit(): void {
        // Unschedule everything
        this.unscheduleAllCallbacks();

        // Remove all children
        this.removeAllChildren(true);  // true = cleanup

        super.onExit();
    }

    update(dt: number): void {
        // Game logic
    }
}

// Scene transition cleans up old scene
const newScene = new cc.Scene();
newScene.addChild(new MenuLayer());

// replaceScene removes and cleans up the old scene
cc.director.runScene(newScene);

// For LayerMultiplex, release unused layers
const multiplex = new cc.LayerMultiplex(layer1, layer2);
// When done with layer1 permanently:
multiplex.switchToAndReleaseMe(1);  // releases layer1
```

Key points:
- `cc.director.runScene` replaces the current scene and triggers cleanup on the old one
- Override `onExit()` for custom cleanup (unschedule, remove listeners)
- `removeAllChildren(true)` cleans up children recursively
- Use `switchToAndReleaseMe` in `cc.LayerMultiplex` for one-time layers
- Children added with `addChild` are automatically cleaned up when the parent is removed

```typescript
interface TimeOfDayColors {
    startColor: cc.Color;
    endColor: cc.Color;
    startOpacity: number;
    endOpacity: number;
}

const TIME_SCHEMES: Record<string, TimeOfDayColors> = {
    dawn:  { startColor: cc.color(255, 150, 80, 255),  endColor: cc.color(100, 50, 120, 255),  startOpacity: 255, endOpacity: 255 },
    day:   { startColor: cc.color(135, 206, 250, 255), endColor: cc.color(70, 130, 200, 255),  startOpacity: 255, endOpacity: 255 },
    dusk:  { startColor: cc.color(255, 100, 50, 255),  endColor: cc.color(40, 20, 80, 255),   startOpacity: 255, endOpacity: 255 },
    night: { startColor: cc.color(10, 10, 40, 255),    endColor: cc.color(0, 0, 10, 255),     startOpacity: 255, endOpacity: 200 }
};

class DayNightCycle extends cc.Layer {
    private sky: cc.LayerGradient;
    private currentScheme: string = 'day';

    constructor() {
        super();
        this.init();
    }

    init(): boolean {
        const scheme = TIME_SCHEMES[this.currentScheme];
        this.sky = new cc.LayerGradient(
            scheme.startColor,
            scheme.endColor,
            cc.p(0, -1)
        );
        this.addChild(this.sky);
        return true;
    }

    transitionTo(timeOfDay: string): void {
        const scheme = TIME_SCHEMES[timeOfDay];
        if (!scheme) return;

        this.currentScheme = timeOfDay;
        this.sky.setStartColor(scheme.startColor);
        this.sky.setEndColor(scheme.endColor);
        this.sky.setStartOpacity(scheme.startOpacity);
        this.sky.setEndOpacity(scheme.endOpacity);
    }

    getTimeOfDay(): string {
        return this.currentScheme;
    }
}

// Usage:
const cycle = new DayNightCycle();
scene.addChild(cycle, -1);
cycle.transitionTo('dawn');
cycle.transitionTo('night');
```

Four time-of-day presets are stored as color configurations. `transitionTo` updates the gradient's start/end colors and opacities. The gradient direction `cc.p(0, -1)` creates a natural top-to-bottom sky effect. For smooth animated transitions, you could interpolate the color values over time using `scheduleUpdate`.

```typescript
class AnimatedGradientBg extends cc.Layer {
    private grad: cc.LayerGradient;
    private time: number = 0;

    private static readonly SPEED = 0.3;

    constructor() {
        super();
        this.init();
    }

    init(): boolean {
        this.grad = new cc.LayerGradient(
            cc.color(100, 50, 200, 255),
            cc.color(20, 10, 60, 255),
            cc.p(0, -1)
        );
        this.addChild(this.grad);
        this.scheduleUpdate();
        return true;
    }

    update(dt: number): void {
        this.time += dt * AnimatedGradientBg.SPEED;

        const r1 = Math.floor(100 + 50 * Math.sin(this.time));
        const g1 = Math.floor(50 + 40 * Math.sin(this.time * 0.7));
        const b1 = Math.floor(200 + 55 * Math.sin(this.time * 0.5));

        const r2 = Math.floor(20 + 15 * Math.sin(this.time * 0.8));
        const g2 = Math.floor(10 + 10 * Math.sin(this.time * 0.6));
        const b2 = Math.floor(60 + 30 * Math.sin(this.time * 0.4));

        this.grad.setStartColor(cc.color(r1, g1, b1, 255));
        this.grad.setEndColor(cc.color(r2, g2, b2, 255));

        // Slowly rotate gradient direction
        const angle = this.time * 0.2;
        this.grad.setVector(cc.p(
            Math.sin(angle) * 0.3,
            -1 + Math.cos(angle) * 0.2
        ));
    }
}

const scene = new cc.Scene();
scene.addChild(new AnimatedGradientBg(), -1);
cc.director.runScene(scene);
```

The `update` loop uses sine waves at different frequencies to create a smooth, organic color shift. Each RGB channel oscillates independently. The gradient direction also subtly rotates using `setVector`, creating a dynamic parallax-like movement. The `SPEED` constant controls overall animation speed.

